ion-2/',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2010-01-19 11:07:30','2010-01-19 11:07:30','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n		{\r\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n		};\r\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n</pre>\r\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that you can go back to the landing page and select a new country.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','draft','open','open','','using-cookies-to-redirect-a-user-to-the-last-page-they-visted','','','2010-06-29 14:27:32','2010-06-29 13:27:32','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=18',0,'post','',0),(19,1,'2010-01-19 11:00:19','2010-01-19 11:00:19','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\n\nCode for the country home page template\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n					{\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n					};\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\n\n	if (!IsPostBack)\n		DataBind();\n}</pre>\nCode for the global home page','','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision','','','2010-01-19 11:00:19','2010-01-19 11:00:19','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/19/18-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(20,1,'2010-01-19 11:06:58','2010-01-19 11:06:58','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\n\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n					{\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n					};\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\n\n	if (!IsPostBack)\n		DataBind();\n}</pre>\n<strong>Code for the global home page</strong>\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	//redirect away from this map page to the last country page\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\n	var isNotAdminUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsadmin\");\n	var isNotEditUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsedit\");\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\n\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; isNotAdminUrl &amp;&amp; isNotEditUrl &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\n	{\n		//redirect to last country page\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\n	}\n}</pre>\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that:\n<ol>\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from a country home page they are not sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\n</ol>\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.','','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-2','','','2010-01-19 11:06:58','2010-01-19 11:06:58','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/19/18-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(21,1,'2010-03-27 13:24:02','2010-03-27 13:24:02','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n		{\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n		};\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);</pre>\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\n\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\n	{\n		//redirect to last country page\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\n	}</pre>\nThe important part in the code abo