ot sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.<!--more-->','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-7','','','2010-02-27 20:58:59','2010-02-27 20:58:59','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/18-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(27,1,'2009-11-17 14:03:04','2009-11-17 14:03:04','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\r\n\r\nHere\'s what I did:\r\n\r\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\r\n\r\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-3','','','2009-11-17 14:03:04','2009-11-17 14:03:04','',3,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2009/11/17/3-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(28,1,'2010-02-27 21:46:46','2010-02-27 21:46:46','<p>I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s what I did:</p>\r\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\r\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\r\n','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-4','','','2010-02-27 21:46:46','2010-02-27 21:46:46','',3,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/3-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(29,1,'2010-02-27 22:28:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I spoke to a good friend of mine last week who told me his fiancee wanted to build a website and maybe try to get into web design or development.\r\n\r\nAs a web developer there was a huge amount of advice I wanted to give him there and then, and of course he was completely lost after the first 30 seconds!\r\n\r\nSo I\'m going to make a list here of some of the most important things a starting-out web developer should know about.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Standards</li>\r\n	<li>Browser compatibility and testing</li>\r\n	<li>Firefox addons</li>\r\n	<li>Source control</li>\r\n</ul>','Web development tools','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-02-27 22:28:52','2010-02-27 22:28:52','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=29',0,'post','',0),(30,1,'2010-02-27 22:16:42','2010-02-27 22:16:42','I spoke to a good friend of mine last week who told me his fiancee wanted to build a website and maybe try to get into web design or development.\n\nAs a web developer there was a huge amount of advice I wanted to give him there and then, and of course he was completely lost after the first 30 seconds!\n\nSo I\'m going to make a list here of some of the most important things a starting-out web developer should know about.\n<ul>\n	<li>Standards</li>\n	<li>Browser compatibility and testing</li>\n	<li>Firefox addons</li>\n	<li>Source control</li>\n</ul>','Web development tools','','inherit','open','open','','29-revision','','','2010-02-27 22:16:42','2010-02-27 22:16:42','',29,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/29-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2010-03-27 13:56:56','2010-03-27 13:56:56','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else when I don\'t want them to be.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\r\n\r\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\r\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis will create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\r\n\r\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','publish','open','open','','branching-with-tortoise-svn','','','2010-07-03 10:49:54','2010-07-03 09:49:54','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=31',0,'post','',0),(32,1,'2010-03-27 13:24:01','2010-03-27 13:24:01','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\n\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\n\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.htm