r above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-12','','','2010-04-19 17:41:52','2010-04-19 16:41:52','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/19/50-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2010-04-22 11:45:56','2010-04-22 10:45:56','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h2><span styl