 new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\" which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top of left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode o the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNow I need a page template so I can start adding some content to the CMS! I\'ve added a new template file using the EPiServer Visual Studio template. This added an aspx file to the project (which inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). A popup box asked me if I\'d like to register the page type, I clicked \"no\", and did this myself in EPiServer admin mode after renaming the file. I also added a long string property for some text.\r\n\r\nUseful resources:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>','Creating an EPiServer 6 Site','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-11','','','2010-07-09 23:44:55','2010-07-09 22:44:55','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/09/149-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(170,1,'2010-07-11 08:45:08','2010-07-11 07:45:08','The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\r\n\r\nI\'m going to create a css drop-down menu showing 2 levels of pages. This is the code for the PageTree control:\r\n<pre class=\"brush: xhtml\">&lt;EPiServer:PageTree ShowRootPage=\"false\" PageLink=\"&lt;%#PageReference.StartPage %&gt;\" NumberOfLevels=\"2\" ExpandAll=\"true\" runat=\"server\" ID=\"PrimaryNavigation\"&gt;\r\n	&lt;IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;EPiServer:Property ID=\"Property1\" PropertyName=\"PageLink\" runat=\"server\" /&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n&lt;/EPiServer:PageTree&gt;</pre>\r\nNote the properties in the parent element - ShowRootPage (whether to show the start page), PageLink (the starting page for the menu), ExpandAll (renders a menu item for every page), NumberOfLevels (the number of levels to render out).\r\n\r\nI\'ve put this on the start page template of my EPiServer site as it\'s just an exercise. Ideally it would be contained in an ascx user control that would be referenced from the master page of the site. So this renders all the markup I need for my menu, it\'s simply HTML lists.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-174\" title=\"primary-navigation-lists\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-lists-600x366.jpg\" alt=\"The primary navigation is rendered as a HTML lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"366\" />\r\n\r\nFirebug shows the HTML lists rendered by the PageTree control and my templates.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-175\" title=\"primary-nav-markup-in-firebug\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-nav-markup-in-firebug-600x430.jpg\" alt=\"Firebug shows the markup of the navigation lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"430\" />\r\n\r\nNext it\'s just a matter of applying some css style to get the menu looking and behaving a bit more like a menu. I\'ve wrapped the PageTree control with a div element with an id of \"priary-nav\" so I can target it with css rules.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:css\">div#primary-nav ul\r\n{\r\n	list-style-image: none;\r\n	list-style-position: outside;\r\n	list-style-type: none;\r\n	margin: 0;\r\n	padding: 0;\r\n	text-align:center;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li\r\n	{\r\n		float: left;\r\n		background-color: #ccc;\r\n		width:100px;\r\n		text-align:center;\r\n	}\r\n		div#primary-nav li a\r\n		{\r\n			padding:5px;\r\n			display:block;\r\n		}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li ul\r\n{\r\n	width:100px;\r\n	position: absolute;\r\n	left: -999em;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li ul li\r\n	{\r\n		background-color: #eee;\r\n	}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li:hover ul\r\n{\r\n	left: auto;\r\n}</pre>\r\nAnd with style applied the menu looks like this:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-176\" title=\"primary-navigation-with-css\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-with-css.jpg\" alt=\"The navigation menu with css rules applied\" width=\"369\" height=\"207\" />\r\n\r\nBuilding on this example should enable me to quickly build drop-down menus for a number of scenarios - there are a lot more properties and templates of the PageTree control to explore, and understanding the basics is the first step to building more complex navigation to fit the requirements of a specific site.\r\n\r\nUseful links:\r\n\r\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/','EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation','','publish','open','open','','episerver-pagetree-for-primary-navigation','','','2010-08-22 21:44:43','2010-08-22 20:44:43','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=170',0,'post','',0),(171,1,'2010-07-11 07:29:34','2010-07-11 06:29:34','The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\n<pre class=\"brush:xhtml\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div></pre>\nUseful links:\n\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/','EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation','','inherit','open','open','','170-revision','','','2010-07-11 07:29:34','2010-07-11 06:29:34','',170,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/11/170-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(172,1,'2010-07-11 07:34:16','2010-07-11 06:34:16','The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\n\nI\'m going to create a css drop-down