er PageTree for primary navigation','','inherit','open','open','','170-revision-10','','','2010-08-22 08:47:52','2010-08-22 07:47:52','',170,'http://localhost/jsewell_mywordpressblog/index.php/2010/08/22/170-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(199,1,'2010-07-10 22:23:31','2010-07-10 21:23:31','These are the steps Â to create a new EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tools. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\" which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\nUseful resources:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>','Creating an EPiServer 6 Site','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open