pe) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nIn order to maintain maximum control over what is installed on the web server you might try to install the service using the <strong>installutil </strong>program. I tried this approach, I copied the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\" and ran the command:\n\n<strong>installutil EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe</strong>\n\nBut this doesn\'t work and you\'ll get an error:\n\n<strong>No public installers with the RunInstallerAttribute.Yes attribute could be found in the D:\\sites\\jisc-collections.ac.uk\\EPiServerSchedulerService5.2.375.236\\EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe assembly.</strong>\n\nThe scheduler service is not designed to be manually installed like this. As such your only option is to install it using <strong>EPiServerShared.msi</strong> from the EPiServer CMS installation files (available on <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Download/Categories/Products/EPiServer-CMS/\">EPiServer World</a>). This will install and start 3 services and won\'t require you to restart the machine:\n<ul>\n	<li>EPiServer Scheduler Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Log Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Indexing Service</li>\n</ul>\nIt\'s not an ideal solution if you like to maintain absolute control over what is installed on the web server, but it\'s a quick and easy install that does work.','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?','inherit','open','open','','204-autosave','','','2010-09-09 08:54:16','2010-09-09 07:54:16','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/09/204-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(217,1,'2010-08-25 14:01:28','2010-08-25 13:01:28','PageReference has an ID property, PageData does not\n\nPageReference.StartPage gets you the page refrence of the start page (PageReference.RootPage exists too)\n\nGlobal.UrlRewriteProvider.ConvertToExternal - get the friendly URL of a page (there is a method ConvertToInternal too)\n\nExample:\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">UrlBuilder urlBuilder = new UrlBuilder(EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.SiteUrl);</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">Global.UrlRewriteProvider.ConvertToExternal(urlBuilderÂ , page.PageLink, System.Text.UTF8Encoding.UTF8);</div>\n<div>var friendlyUrl -=Â urlBuilder.ToString();</div>','EPiServer snippets','','inherit','open','open','','179-revision-8','','','2010-08-25 14:01:28','2010-08-25 13:01:28','',179,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/25/179-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(218,1,'2010-09-23 15:22:06','2010-09-23 14:22:06','EPiServer Dynamic properties are very useful and it\'s tempting to make generous use of them.\r\n\r\nI\'m working on a feature and trying to decide if I should use dynamic properties or a property on the page type. I\'ve decided to avoid dynamic properties in this case because dynamic properties apply to ALL pages, but they are not necessarily used by all pages.\r\n\r\nCreating a dynamic property for something that is only used by a few page types causes confusion because it can be set on any of the ancestors of a pages, but may only be used by one or a few pages. In cases like this it\'s better to keep the property close to the items it affects.','What\'s wrong with EPiServer Dynamic Properties','A quick note on why dynamic properties are often a bad idea.','publish','open','open','','whats-wrong-with-episerver-dynamic-properties','','','2010-10-26 13:38:11','2010-10-26 12:38:11','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=218',0,'post','',0),(219,1,'2010-09-23 15:21:16','2010-09-23 14:21:16','EPiServer Dynamic properties are very useful and it\'s tempting to make generous use of them.\n\nI\'m working on a feature and trying to decide if I should use dynamic properties or a property on the page type. I\'ve decided to avoid dynamic properties in this case because dynamic properties apply to ALL pages, but they are not necessarily used by all pages.\n\nCreating a dynamic property for something that is only used by a few page types causes confusion because it can be set on any of the ancestors of a pages, but may only be used by one or a few pages. In cases like this it\'s better to keep the property close to the object it affects.','What\'s wrong with EPiServer Dynamic Properties','','inherit','open','open','','218-revision','','','2010-09-23 15:21:16','2010-09-23 14:21:16','',218,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/23/218-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(221,1,'2010-09-28 23:09:57','2010-09-28 22:09:57','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>. Why Git? Well the obvious benefits are speed in downloading from a remote repository, and there are no .svn folders in all the project folders. And it\'s a distributed system that gives you a local repository to work with, so if the remote server is unavailable (or you don\'t have internet access) you can still use your local repository.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>What are public/private keys?</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','publish','open','open','','git-and-the-secure-shell-ssh','','','2010-10-27 22:55:27','2010-10-27 21:55:27','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=221',0,'post','',0),(222,1,'2010-09-28 23:08:52','2010-09-28 22:08:52','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>.\n\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\n<ul>\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\n</ul>\nUsing this system i