s are very useful and it\'s tempting to make generous use of them.\r\n\r\nI\'m working on a feature and trying to decide if I should use dynamic properties or a property on the page type. I\'ve decided to avoid dynamic properties in this case because dynamic properties apply to ALL pages, but they are not necessarily used by all pages.\r\n\r\nCreating a dynamic property for something that is only used by a few page types causes confusion because it can be set on any of the ancestors of a pages, but may only be used by one or a few pages. In cases like this it\'s better to keep the property close to the item it affects.','What\'s wrong with EPiServer Dynamic Properties','A quick note on why dynamic properties are often a bad idea.','inherit','open','open','','218-revision-2','','','2010-09-23 15:22:06','2010-09-23 14:22:06','',218,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/23/218-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(235,1,'2010-10-27 10:09:13','2010-10-27 09:09:13','','EPiServer 6 Direct On-Page Editing','','draft','open','open','','episerver-6-direct-on-page-editing','','','2011-04-04 16:11:29','2011-04-04 15:11:29','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=235',0,'post','',0),(237,1,'2010-10-27 22:45:22','2010-10-27 21:45:22','I had an interesting problem last week when a customer reported that the \"linking pages\" or \"soft links\" feature was not working correctly. This is the warning you get when you try to delete an image that is used somewhere on the site. You can also look at the file summary to see a list of pages that use that file.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-238 alignnone\" title=\"episerver-linking-pages\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-linking-pages.png\" alt=\"Screenshot showing linking pages list\" width=\"530\" height=\"216\" />\r\n\r\nIt turns out that this feature is linked to the page indexing implementation which indexes searchable page properties after a page is published. In this case the property in question had not been set as searchable (via admin mode or <a title=\"More information on using PageTypeBuilder\" href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/01/a-developers-guide-to-pagetypebuilder/\">PageTypeBuilder</a> attribute), which leads to the question of how to get all these page properties indexed without having to republish all the affected pages.\r\n\r\nIt turns out it\'s easy to add pages to the search index via the EPiServer API. I\'ve put the code in a scheduled job so it can be run easily or scheduled.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[ScheduledPlugIn(DisplayName = \"Recreate Page Search Index\", Description = \"Re-adds all pages in the website to the search index.\")]\r\npublic class ReindexingJob : JobBase\r\n{\r\n	public override string Execute()\r\n	{\r\n		var array = new ArrayList();\r\n		var pages = new EPiServer.DataAccess.PageListDB().ListAll();\r\n		foreach (var page in pages)\r\n			array.Add(page.ID);\r\n\r\n		var job = new IndexPageJob((int[])array.ToArray(typeof(int)));\r\n		job.Execute();\r\n\r\n		return String.Format(\"{0} pages have been added to the indexer.\", pages.Count);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThere may be a delay before pages start to be added to the index, which is controlled by the indexingDelayAfterPublish configuration setting in the episerver.config file.\r\n\r\nIndex data is stored in 2 tables, tblKeyword and tblPageKeyword.\r\n\r\nMore information is <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40816\">here on EPiServer World</a>.','Fixing EPiServer soft links','','publish','open','open','','fixing-episerver-soft-links','','','2011-04-04 16:11:54','2011-04-04 15:11:54','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=237',0,'post','',2),(238,1,'2010-10-27 22:15:00','2010-10-27 21:15:00','','episerver-linking-pages','','inherit','open','open','','episerver-linking-pages','','','2010-10-27 22:15:00','2010-10-27 21:15:00','',237,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-l