he remote server is unavailable (or you don\'t have internet access) you can still use your local repository.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-revision-4','','','2010-10-02 11:22:24','2010-10-02 10:22:24','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/02/221-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(247,1,'2010-11-29 20:20:56','2010-11-29 20:20:56','This is my web development learning journal. It\'s a place for me to store useful code and information that I work with so I can refer back to it in the future. It\'s also a learning tool because writing down a problem or solution makes me think about it logically and helps me to understand it.\n\nI\'m a web developer and I work at <a title=\"The Cubeworks site\" href=\"http://www.cubeworks.co.uk\">Cubeworks </a>in <a title=\"Brighton on the map\" href=\"http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=brighton,+uk&amp;sll=53.800651,-4.064941&amp;sspn=20.824402,57.084961&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=Brighton,+East+Sussex,+United+Kingdom&amp;ll=50.819818,-0.131836&amp;spn=22.241089,57.084961&amp;z=5\">Brighton</a>.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-292\" title=\"Jonathan Sewell\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/DSCF3927_small.jpg\" alt=\"Jonathan Sewell\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" />','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-autosave','','','2010-11-29 20:20:56','2010-11-29 20:20:56','',2,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/28/2-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(248,1,'2009-11-13 14:07:02','2009-11-13 14:07:02','This is an example of a WordPress page, you could edit this to put information about yourself or your site so readers know where you are coming from. You can create as many pages like this one or sub-pages as you like and manage all of your