here are some good ones, notably the personalisation features, as well as the really useful auto save feature. But I\'m disappointed with the new \"mark as in use\" feature. Besides the fact that the name doesn\'t roll off the tongue, just from looking at the screen shot I think it has some serious flaws.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-261 alignnone\" title=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/image_10-600x244.png\" alt=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use Button\" width=\"600\" height=\"244\" />\r\n\r\nThe intent of this new feature is to allow \"one editor to let the others know that he/she is working on a piece of content right now\", and this is done by clicking on a button with a red stop sign icon labelled \"Mark as In Use\".  Presumably this will show a notification to any other user who opens the same page for editing. Marking a page as in use \"locks\" the page, but it can be unlocked by other editors (in case the first editor forgets to do it).\r\n\r\nMy first concern is the button, why must the editor click a button? They aren\'t likely to remember to do it, and they\'re less likely to remember to unlock it. I think it makes a lot more sense to automatically flag a page as in use as soon as it\'s opened for editing. And automatically detect when the user has closed edit mode so there are no false notifications. Why clutter the UI with another button (there are 15 tabs/buttons in the screen shot alone)?\r\n\r\nSecondly the concept of locking is flawed if another editor can simply unlock the page, it\'s not a lock if it\'s not lockable right? I think a much simpler concept is simply notification... this page is open by user xyz. Edit it at your peril.\r\n\r\nWhat about direct on-page editing? There is no means to manually mark a page as in use, and will you get a notification that someone has locked the page if you are editing on the page? There seems to be some inconsistency here that could be solved by getting rid of that button.\r\n\r\nAny comments are most welcome!','Forgetting to \"mark as in use\"','','publish','open','open','','forgetting-to-mark-as-in-use','','','2011-04-04 16:11:49','2011-04-04 15:11:49','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=257',0,'post','',6),(258,1,'2010-11-22 12:15:45','2010-11-22 12:15:45','I\'ve just been reading about <a title=\"EPiServer World Blog\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Blogs/Allan-Thran/Dates/2010/11/EPiServer-CMS-6-Release-2/\">the new features in EPiServer 6 R2</a> and there are some good ones, notably the personalisation features, as well as the really useful auto save feature. But I\'m disappointed with the new \"mark as in use\" feature. Besides the fact that the name doesn\'t roll off the tongue, just from looking at the screen shot I think it has some serious flaws.\n\n<img class=\"alignleft\" style=\"margin-right: 10px;\" title=\"Mark as In Use Button\" src=\"http://world.episerver.com/Globals/xmlrpc/20055/2010/11/20/image_10.png\" alt=\"The new Mark as In Use Button\" width=\"400\" height=\"163\" />The intent of this new feature is to allow \"one editor to let the others know that he/she is working on a piece of content right now\", and this is done by clicking on a button with a red stop sign icon labelled \"Mark as In Use\".  Presumably this will show a notification to any other user who opens the same page for editing. Marking a page as in use \"locks\" the page, but it can be unlocked by other editors (in case the first editor forgets to do it).\n\nMy first concern is the button, why must the editor click a button? They aren\'t likely to remember to do it, and they\'re less likely to remember to unlock it. I think it makes a lot more sense to automatically flag a page as in use as soon as it\'s opened for editing.\n\nSecondly the concept of locking is flawed if another editor can simply unlock the page, it\'s not a lock if it\'s not lockable right? I think a much simpler concept is simply notificat