as In Use Button\" src=\"http://world.episerver.com/Globals/xmlrpc/20055/2010/11/20/image_10.png\" alt=\"The new Mark as In Use Button\" width=\"400\" height=\"163\" />The intent of this new feature is to allow \"one editor to let the others know that he/she is working on a piece of content right now\", and this is done by clicking on a button with a red stop sign icon labelled \"Mark as In Use\".  Presumably this will show a notification to any other user who opens the same page for editing. Marking a page as in use \"locks\" the page, but it can be unlocked by other editors (in case the first editor forgets to do it).\r\n\r\nMy first concern is the button, why must the editor click a button? They aren\'t likely to remember to do it, and they\'re less likely to remember to unlock it. I think it makes a lot more sense to automatically flag a page as in use as soon as it\'s opened for editing. And automatically detect when the user has closed edit mode so there are no false notifications.\r\n\r\nSecondly the concept of locking is flawed if another editor can simply unlock the page, it\'s not a lock if it\'s not lockable right? I think a much simpler concept is simply notification... this page is open by user xyz.\r\n\r\nWhat about direct on-page editing? There is no means to manually mark a page as in use, will you get a notification that someone has locked the page if you are editing on the page? There seems to be some inconsistency here that could be solved by getting rid of that button.','Forgetting to \"mark as in use\"','','inherit','open','open','','257-revision-4','','','2010-11-22 12:26:09','2010-11-22 12:26:09','',257,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/22/257-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(263,1,'2010-11-22 12:32:59','2010-11-22 12:32:59','I\'ve just been reading about <a title=\"EPiServer World Blog\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Blogs/Allan-Thran/Dates/2010/11/EPiServer-CMS-6-Release-2/\">the new features in EPiServer 6 R2</a> and there are some good ones, notably the personalisation features, as well as the really useful auto save feature. But I\'m disappointed with the new \"mark as in use\" feature. Besides the fact that the name doesn\'t roll off the tongue, just from looking at the screen shot I think it has some serious flaws.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-261 alignnone\" title=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/image_10-600x244.png\" alt=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use Button\" width=\"600\" height=\"244\" />\r\n\r\nThe intent of this new feature is to allow \"one editor to let the others know that he/she is working on a piece of content right now\", and this is done by clicking on a button with a red stop sign icon labelled \"Mark as In Use\".  Presumably this will show a notification to any other user who opens the same page for editing. Marking a page as in use \"locks\" the page, but it can be unlocked by other editors (in case the first editor forgets to do it).\r\n\r\nMy first concern is the button, why must the editor click a button? They aren\'t likely to remember to do it, and they\'re less likely to remember to unlock it. I think it makes a lot more sense to automatically flag a page as in use as soon as it\'s opened for editing. And automatically detect when the user has closed edit mode so there are no false notifications. Why clutter the UI with another button (there are 15 tabs/buttons in the screen shot alone)?\r\n\r\nSecondly the concept of locking is flawed if another editor can simply unlock the page, it\'s not a lock if it\'s not lockable right? I think a much simpler concept is simply notification... this page is open by user xyz. Edit it at your peril.\r\n\r\nWhat about direct on-page editing? There is no means to manually mark a page as in use, and will you get a notification that someone has locked the page if you are editing on the page? There seems to be some inconsistency here that could be solved by getting rid of that button.\r\n\r\nAny comments are most welcome!','Forgetting to \"mark as in use\"','','inherit','open','open','','257-revision-5','','','2010-11-22 12:32:59','2010-11-22 12:32:59','',257,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/22/257-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(264,1,'2010-11-26 11:56:26','2010-11-26 11:56:26','I need to install EPiServer mail on an existing site. The deployment centre is great for quickly setting up a new site, but not for the way we work. We prefer to have all the EPiServer files in the website, rather than in Windows \"Program Files\". And all the required libraries in a separate library folder and referenced by the Visual Studio project. Then the whole lot can be checked in to source control, pulled down by any other developer on any machine, and crucially by our build server.\r\n\r\nI\'ve installed a brand new site on my machine (EPiServer 6.0.530.0), created a copy of it, then installed EPiServer mail on the new site. I can then use <a title=\"Scooter Softeware\" href=\"http://www.scootersoftware.com\">Beyond Compare</a> to see what the Deployment Centre has done . Here are the results:\r\n<h3>2 new folders have been added</h3>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-additional-files\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-additional-files.png\" alt=\"Screen shot of new folders\" width=\"256\" height=\"548\" />\r\n\r\nA new \"EPiServer\" folder and a new \"EPiServerMail\" folder have been added.\r\n<h3>A new database and connection string</h3>\r\nA new database was created for EPiServer mail, and a connection string added to connectionStrings.config.\r\n<h3>A new config file EPiServerMail.config</h3>\r\n<pre>&lt;episerver.mail&gt;\r\n    &lt;sites&gt;\r\n        &lt;site siteId=\"*\"&gt;\r\n            &lt;broker brokerName=\"\" brokerHostname=\"episervermail.episerver.com\" brokerIP=\"217.114.81.159\" /&gt;\r\n            &lt;editor defaultFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" defaultFromName=\"EPiServer Mail\" goMailUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/GoMail.aspx\" mailFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" goMailImageUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/pixel.gif\" encoding=\"iso-8859-1\" editorWebServiceUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/EPiServerMailService.asmx\" unsubscribeUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/Unsubscribe.aspx?rid=§recipientId§&amp;amp;mid=§messageId§\" /&gt;\r\n            &lt;smtpServer name=\"localhost\" port=\"25\" timeout=\"60\" authMode=\"None\" account=\"\" password=\"\" /&gt;\r\n        &lt;/site&gt;\r\n    &lt;/sites&gt;\r\n&lt;/episerver.mail&gt;</pre>\r\n<h3>Additions and changes to the bin folder</h3>\r\nNew files are shown in blue, changed files are shown in red.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-268\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-bin-changes\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-bin-changes.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"374\" height=\"766\" />\r\n\r\nThe changed files have all changed from version <strong>6.0.318.113</strong> to<strong> 6.1.79.0</strong>.\r\n<h3>Web.config Changes</h3>\r\nThese changes are too many to reproduce here so I\'ll summarise and upload the 2 config files.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>new configuration sections registered</li>\r\n	<li>new nhibernate section</li>\r\n	<li>new hibernate-configuration section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.common section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.search section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.mail section</li>\r\n	<li>updated assembly bindings for updated .dll files (EPiServer.Data.Cache etc)</li>\r\n	<li>new assembly bindings (EPiServer.Mail.Core etc)</li>\r\n	<li>new role and membership providers registered (EPiServerCommonRoleProvider and EPiServerCommonMembershipProvider)</li>\r\n	<li>pages section, change enableEventValidation to false</li>\r\n	<li>new modules in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;modules&gt;</li>\r\n	<li>new handlers in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;handlers&gt;</li>\r\n	<li>new location sections for EPiServerMail and EPiServerMail/Public</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a title=\"web.config before mail installation\" href=\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.original\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.original</a>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"web.config after mail installation\" href=\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.mail\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.mail</a>','Install EPiServer Mail Manually','','publish','open','open','','install-episerver-mail-manually','','','2011-04-04 16:11:45','2011-04-04 15:11:45','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=264',0,'post','',0),(265,1,'2010-11-26 10:09:08','2010-11-26 10:09:08','','EPiServer-mail-additional-files','','inherit','open','open','','episerver-mail-additional-files','','','2010-11-26 10:09:08','2010-11-26 10:09:08','',264,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-additional-files.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(266,1,'2010-11-26 10:14:06','2010-11-26 10:14:06','I need to install EPiServer mail on an existing site. The deployment centre is great for quickly setting up a new site, but not for the way we work. We prefer to have all the EPiServer files in the website, rather than in Windows \"Program Files\". And all the required libraries in a separate library folder and referenced by the Visual Studio project. Then the whole lot can be checked in to source control, pulled down by any other developer on any machine, and crucially by our build server.\n\nI\'ve installed a brand new site on my machine, created a copy of it, then installed EPiServer mail on the new site. I can then use <a title=\"Scooter Softeware\" href=\"http://www.scootersoftware.com\">Beyond Compare</a> to see what the Deployment Centre has done. Here are the results:\n<h3>2