ttonUpdate.UniqueID;</pre>\r\nMore information:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://geekswithblogs.net/ranganh/archive/2006/04/12/74951.aspx\">http://geekswithblogs.net/ranganh/archive/2006/04/12/74951.aspx</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://imar.spaanjaars.com/374/how-do-i-set-the-defaultfocus-or-defaultbutton-in-a-page-based-on-a-master-page-in-aspnet-20\">http://imar.spaanjaars.com/374/how-do-i-set-the-defaultfocus-or-defaultbutton-in-a-page-based-on-a-master-page-in-aspnet-20</a>','Default form button problem','','inherit','open','open','','322-revision-2','','','2011-01-11 16:13:15','2011-01-11 16:13:15','',322,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/01/11/322-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(325,1,'2011-01-13 22:17:13','2011-01-13 22:17:13','One of the problems with the default install of EPiServer 6 is that you can\'t use a relative path for virtual path providers (which map virtual URLs to files in the file manager). This means that while I have these files at <strong>D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP</strong> and another developer pulls my code out of source control they will have a problem because they put the project in <strong>F:\\development\\LatestEPiServerProject</strong>.\r\n\r\nWe can avoid these problems by using a relative path in the .config file. So:\r\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\r\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\r\ntype=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,EPiServer\"\r\n<strong><em>physicalPath=\"D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP\\Documents</em>\"</strong> /&gt;</pre>\r\nbecomes:\r\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\r\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\r\n<strong><em>type=\"MyEPiServerExtensions.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,MyEPiServerExtensions\"\r\nphysicalPath=\"~\\..\\VPP\\Documents\"</em></strong> /&gt;</pre>\r\nI need to go up a directory and back down to the VPP folder, I have folder structure:\r\n\r\nD:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP\\Documents\r\nD:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\Site\\\r\n\r\nThe new provider type is simply a thin wrapper that converts relative paths to physical paths that the EPiServer implementation can continue to work with.\r\n\r\nHere is the code:\r\n\r\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/778715.js?file=VirtualPathVersioningProvider.cs\"></script>\r\n\r\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/778715.js?file=VirtualPathProviderExtensions.cs\"></script>','Use a relative path with Virtual Path Providers','','publish','open','open','','use-a-relative-path-with-virtual-path-providers','','','2011-04-04 16:10:52','2011-04-04 15:10:52','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=325',0,'post','',1),(326,1,'2011-01-13 22:16:54','2011-01-13 22:16:54','One of the problems with the default install of EPiServer 6 is that you can\'t use a relative path for virtual path providers (which map virtual URLs to files in the file manager). This means that while I have these files at <strong>D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP</strong> and another developer pulls my code out of source control they will have a problem because they put the project in <strong>F:\\development\\LatestEPiServerProject</strong>.\n\nWe can avoid these problems by using a relative path in the .config file. So:\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\ntype=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,EPiServer\"\n<strong>physicalPath=\"D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP\\Documents\"</strong> /&gt;</pre>\nbecomes:\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\n<strong>type=\"MyEPiServerExtensions.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,MyEPiServerExtensions\"</strong>\n<strong>physicalPath=\"~\\