\nD:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\Site\\\r\n\r\nThe new provider type is simply a thin wrapper that converts relative paths to physical paths that the EPiServer implementation can continue to work with.\r\n\r\nHere is the code:\r\n\r\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/778715.js?file=VirtualPathProviderExtensions.cs\"></script>','Use a relative path with Virtual Path Providers','','inherit','open','open','','325-revision-4','','','2011-04-04 07:50:35','2011-04-04 06:50:35','',325,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/04/325-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(340,1,'2010-11-29 19:08:55','2010-11-29 19:08:55','I\'m creating a demo site of EPiServer 6 CMS using the deployment centre to create the website, then opening it in Visual Studio. That all works until I set the project to use Visual Studio\'s development server (the web server is running on IIS 6). I get a 404 error on the dashboard as soon as I switch to using the development server.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-281\" title=\"episerver-resource-not-found\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/episerver-resource-not-found.png\" alt=\"The resource cannot be found\" width=\"662\" height=\"274\" />\r\n\r\nThe problem is that the Visual Studio development server runs in classic mode (like IIS 6) and the website the Deployment Centre created is designed for Integrated Mode (IIS 7). There are apparently a few more symptoms of this including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>EPiServer Admin Mode returning a 404 error page</li>\r\n	<li>Login page  returning a 404 error page</li>\r\n	<li>No images are shown on the site</li>\r\n	<li>The right-click context menu is not available</li>\r\n	<li>JavaScript or JQuery errors on the page</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTo fix this I manually converted the web.config file to work for IIS 6 (massive pain in the neck!). I <strong>changed all &lt;system.webServer&gt; elements to &lt;system.web&gt; </strong>and for the sub elements, <strong>changed all &lt;handlers&gt; elements to &lt;httpHandlers&gt; and &lt;modules&gt; to &lt;httpModules&gt;</strong>. Also removed all attributes (in all child elements) except path, verb and type.\r\n\r\nI also had to add the following to &lt;httpHandlers&gt;:\r\n\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.png\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.jpg\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.jpeg\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.css\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.js\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;add path=\"*.gif\" verb=\"GET,HEAD\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.StaticFileHandler, EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nThe EPiServer installation files seem to include a version of the web.config for IIS 6 and one for IIS 7. There are located in <strong>C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\</strong> on my machine.\r\n\r\nI found the following sites useful when looking into this:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40971\">http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40971</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40971\"></a><a href=\"http://www.markeverard.com/blog/2010/05/21/default-episerver-web-configs-for-iis6-and-iis7/\">http://www.markeverard.com/blog/2010/05/21/default-episerver-web-configs-for-iis6-and-iis7/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://epiwiki.se/configuration/webconfig-iis7-to-iis6\"></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://epiwiki.se/configuration/webconfig-iis7-to-iis6\">http://epiwiki.se/configuration/webconfig-iis7-to-iis6</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-SP1/Changes-Between-IIS6-and-IIS7/\"></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-SP1/Changes-Between-IIS6-and-IIS7/\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-SP1/Changes-Between-IIS6-and-IIS7/</a>','EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio development server','','inherit','open','open','','280-revision-10','','','2010-11-29 19:08:55','2010-11-29 19:08:55','',280,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/29/280-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(342,1,'2011-04-04 10:58:02','2011-04-04 09:58:02','One of the problems with the default install of EPiServer 6 is that you can\'t use a relative path for virtual path providers (which map virtual URLs to files in the file manager). This means that while I have these files at <strong>D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP</strong> and another developer pulls my code out of source control they will have a problem because they put the project in <strong>F:\\development\\LatestEPiServerProject</strong>.\r\n\r\nWe can avoid these problems by using a relative path in the .config file. So:\r\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\r\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\r\ntype=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,EPiServer\"\r\n<strong><em>physicalPath=\"D:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP\\Documents</em>\"</strong> /&gt;</pre>\r\nbecomes:\r\n<pre>&lt;add showInFileManager=\"true\" virtualName=\"Documents\" virtualPath=\"~/Documents/\"\r\nbypassAccessCheck=\"false\" maxVersions=\"5\" name=\"SiteDocuments\"\r\n<strong><em>type=\"MyEPiServerExtensions.VirtualPathVersioningProvider,MyEPiServerExtensions\"\r\nphysicalPath=\"~\\..\\VPP\\Documents\"</em></strong> /&gt;</pre>\r\nI need to go up a directory and back down to the VPP folder, I have folder structure:\r\n\r\nD:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\VPP\\Documents\r\nD:\\LatestEPiServerProject\\Site\\\r\n\r\nThe new provider type is simply a thin wrapper that converts relative paths to physical paths that the EPiServer implementation can continue to work with.\r\n\r\nHere is the code:\r\n\r\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/778715.js?file=VirtualPathVersioningProvider.cs\"></script>\r\n\r\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/778715.js?file=VirtualPathProviderExtensions.cs\"></script>','Use a relative path with Virtual Path Providers','','inherit','open','open','','325-revision-5','','','2011-04-04 10:58:02','2011-04-04 09:58:02','',325,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/04/325-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(343,1,'2010-10-27 10:09:13','2010-10-27 09:09:13','','EPiServer 6 Direct On-Page Editing','','inherit','open','open','','235-revision','','','2010-10-27 10:09:13','2010-10-27 09:09:13','',235,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/27/235-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(344,1,'2011-04-04 16:11:26','2011-04-04 15:11:26','','EPiServer 6 Direct On-Page Editing','','inherit','open','open','','235-revision-2','','','2011-04-04 16:11:26','2011-04-04 15:11:26','',235,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/04/235-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(345,1,'2010-12-06 18:21:54','2010-12-06 18:21:54','EPiServer has a page about <a title=\"EPiServer exam knowledge areas\" href=\"http://www.episerver.com/en/Education/EPiServer-Certified--Developer/Knowledge-Areas/\">the areas you need to cover for the exam</a>.\r\n\r\nThere is <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/556221\">a Stackoverflow thread about the version 5 exam</a> that has some useful information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Some blog posts about the exam:</strong>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Rouslan Minasian\'s post\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Blogs/Rouslan-Minasian/Dates/2010/8/EPiServer-Certification/\">EPiServer Certification</a>, Rouslan Minasian\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Fredrick Haglund\'s post\" href=\"http://blog.fredrikhaglund.se/blog/2008/11/30/how-to-become-a-episerver-ceritified-developer/\">How to become a EPiServer Ceritified Developer</a>, Fredrik Haglund.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Mikael Lundin\'s post\" href=\"http://mint.litemedia.se/2008/11/29/episerver-cms-5-certified-developer/\">EPiServer CMS 5 Certified Developer</a>, Mikael Lundin\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Björn Sållarp\'s post\" href=\"http://blog.sallarp.com/episerver-cms-5-certified/\">EPiServer CMS 5 Certified!</a>, Björn Sållarp\r\n\r\nWhen I was preparing for the exam I re-read the administrator and editor manuals, the developer documentation in the SDK, and the tech notes. The tech notes form the bulk of the material and there are a lot of them so it\'s worth prioritising them somehow.','EPiServer 6 exam bookmarks','','inherit','open','open','','294-revision-4','','','2010-12-06 18:21:54','2010-12-06 18:21:54','',294,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/12/06/294-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(346,1,'2010-11-26 13:30:11','2010-11-26 13:30:11','I need to install EPiServer mail on an existing site. The deployment centre is great for quickly setting up a new site, but not for the way we work. We prefer to have all the EPiServer files in the website, rather than in Windows \"Program Files\". And all the required libraries in a separate library folder and referenced by the Visual Studio project. Then the whole lot can be checked in to source control, pulled down by any other developer on any machine, and crucially by our build server.\r\n\r\nI\'ve installed a brand new site on my machine (EPiServer 6.0.530.0), created a copy of it, then installed EPiServer mail on the new site. I can then use <a title=\"Scooter Softeware\" href=\"http://www.scootersoftware.com\">Beyond Compare</a> to see what the Deployment Centre has done . Here are the results:\r\n<h3>2 new folders have been added</h3>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-additional-files\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-additional-files.png\" alt=\"Screen shot of new folders\" width=\"256\" height=\"548\" />\r\n\r\nA new \"EPiServer\" folder and a new \"EPiServerMail\" folder have been added.\r\n<h3>A new database and connection string</h3>\r\nA new database was created for EPiServer mail, and a connection string added to connectionStrings.config.\r\n<h3>A new config file EPiServerMail.config</h3>\r\n<pre>&lt;episerver.mail&gt;\r\n    &lt;sites&gt;\r\n        &lt;site siteId=\"*\"&gt;\r\n            &lt;broker brokerName=\"\" brokerHostname=\"episervermail.episerver.com\" brokerIP=\"217.114.81.159\" /&gt;\r\n            &lt;editor defaultFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" defaultFromName=\"EPiServer Mail\" goMailUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/GoMail.aspx\" mailFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" goMailImageUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/pixel.gif\" encoding=\"iso-8859-1\" editorWebServiceUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/EPiServerMailService.asmx\" unsubscribeUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/Unsubscribe.aspx?rid=§recipientId§&amp;amp;mid=§messageId§\" /&gt;\r\n            &lt;smtpServer name=\"localhost\" port=\"25\" timeout=\"60\" authMode=\"None\" account=\"\" password=\"\" /&gt;\r\n        &lt;/site&gt;\r\n    &lt;/sites&gt;\r\n&lt;/episerver.mail&gt;</pre>\r\n<h3>Additions and changes to the bin folder</h3>\r\nNew files are shown in blue, changed files are shown in red.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-268\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-bin-changes\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-bin-changes.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"374\" height=\"766\" />\r\n\r\nThe changed files have all changed from version <strong>6.0.318.113</strong> to<strong> 6.1.79.0</strong>.\r\n<h3>Web.config Changes</h3>\r\nThese changes are too many to reproduce here so I\'ll summarise and upload the 2 config files.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>new configuration sections registered</li>\r\n	<li>new nhibernate section</li>\r\n	<li>new hibernate-configuration section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.common section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.search section</li>\r\n	<li>new episerver.mail section</li>\r\n	<li>updated assembly bindings for updated .dll files (EPiServer.Data.Cache etc)</li>\r\n	<li>new assembly bindings (EPiServer.Mail.Core etc)</li>\r\n	<li>new role and membership providers registered (EPiServerCommonRoleProvider and EPiServerCommonMembershipProvider)</li>\r\n	<li>pages section, change enableEventValidation to false</li>\r\n	<li>new modules in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;modules&gt;</li>\r\n	<li>new handlers in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;handlers&gt;</li>\r\n	<li>new location sections for EPiServerMail and EPiServerMail/Public</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a title=\"web.config before mail installation\" href=\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.original\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.original</a>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"web.config after mail installation\" href=\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.mail\">https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/js-jonathan/blog+downloads/web.config.mail</a>','Install EPiServer Mail Manually','','inherit','open','open','','264-revision-13','','','2010-11-26 13:30:11','2010-11-26 13:30:11','',264,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/26/264-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(347,1,'2010-11-22 16:13:12','2010-11-22 16:13:12','I\'ve just been reading about <a title=\"EPiServer World Blog\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Blogs/Allan-Thran/Dates/2010/11/EPiServer-CMS-6-Release-2/\">the new features in EPiServer 6 R2</a> and there are some good ones, notably the personalisation features, as well as the really useful auto save feature. But I\'m disappointed with the new \"mark as in use\" feature. Besides the fact that the name doesn\'t roll off the tongue, just from looking at the screen shot I think it has some serious flaws.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-261 alignnone\" title=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/image_10-600x244.png\" alt=\"EPiServer Mark as In Use Button\" width=\"600\" height=\"244\" />\r\n\r\nThe intent of this new feature is to allow \"one editor to let the others know that he/she is working on a piece of content right now\", and this is done by clicking on a button with a red stop sign icon labelled \"Mark as In Use\".  Presumably this will show a notification to any other user who opens the same page for editing. Marking a page as in use \"locks\" the page, but it can be unlocked by other editors (in case the first editor forgets to do it).\r\n\r\nMy first concern is the button, why must the editor click a button? They aren\'t likely to remember to do it, and they\'re less likely to remember to unlock it. I think it makes a lot more sense to automatically flag a page as in use as soon as it\'s opened for editing. And automatically detect when the user has closed edit mode so there are no false notifications. Why clutter the UI with another button (there are 15 tabs/buttons in the screen shot alone)?\r\n\r\nSecondly the concept of locking is flawed if another editor can simply unlock the page, it\'s not a lock if it\'s not lockable right? I think a much simpler concept is simply notification... this page is open by user xyz. Edit it at your peril.\r\n\r\nWhat about direct on-page editing? There is no means to manually mark a page as in use, and will you get a notification that someone has locked the page if you are editing on the page? There seems to be some inconsistency here that could be solved by getting rid of that button.\r\n\r\nAny comments are most welcome!','Forgetting to \"mark as in use\"','','inherit','open','open','','257-revision-6','','','2010-11-22 16:13:12','2010-11-22 16:13:12','',257,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/22/257-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(348,1,'2010-10-27 22:54:37','2010-10-27 21:54:37','I had an interesting problem last week when a customer reported that the \"linking pages\" or \"soft links\" feature was not working correctly. This is the warning you get when you try to delete an image that is used somewhere on the site. You can also look at the file summary to see a list of pages that use that file.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-238 alignnone\" title=\"episerver-linking-pages\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-linking-pages.png\" alt=\"Screenshot showing linking pages list\" width=\"530\" height=\"216\" />\r\n\r\nIt turns out that this feature is linked to the page indexing implementation which indexes searchable page properties after a page is published. In this case the property in question had not been set as searchable (via admin mode or <a title=\"More information on using PageTypeBuilder\" href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/01/a-developers-guide-to-pagetypebuilder/\">PageTypeBuilder</a> attribute), which leads to the question of how to get all these page properties indexed without having to republish all the affected pages.\r\n\r\nIt turns out it\'s easy to add pages to the search index via the EPiServer API. I\'ve put the code in a scheduled job so it can be run easily or scheduled.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[ScheduledPlugIn(DisplayName = \"Recreate Page Search Index\", Description = \"Re-adds all pages in the website to the search index.\")]\r\npublic class ReindexingJob : JobBase\r\n{\r\n	public override string Execute()\r\n	{\r\n		var array = new ArrayList();\r\n		var pages = new EPiServer.DataAccess.PageListDB().ListAll();\r\n		foreach (var page in pages)\r\n			array.Add(page.ID);\r\n\r\n		var job = new IndexPageJob((int[])array.ToArray(typeof(int)));\r\n		job.Execute();\r\n\r\n		return String.Format(\"{0} pages have been added to the indexer.\", pages.Count);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThere may be a delay before pages start to be added to the index, which is controlled by the indexingDelayAfterPublish configuration setting in the episerver.config file.\r\n\r\nIndex data is stored in 2 tables, tblKeyword and tblPageKeyword.\r\n\r\nMore information is <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40816\">here on EPiServer World</a>.','Fixing EPiServer soft links','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision-7','','','2010-10-27 22:54:37','2010-10-27 21:54:37','',237,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/27/237-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(349,1,'2011-01-11 16:16:28','2011-01-11 16:16:28','Just had to fix a problem with an ASP.NET webforms site where hitting enter in a form took the user to the search results page. The site search button at the top of the page was being selected as the default button.\r\n\r\nThe solution is to set the \"DefaultButton\" property of the form:\r\n<pre>Page.Form.DefaultButton = buttonUpdate.UniqueID;</pre>\r\nMore information:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://geekswithblogs.net/ranganh/archive/2006/04/12/74951.aspx\">http://geekswithblogs.net/ranganh/archive/2006/04/12/74951.aspx</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://imar.spaanjaars.com/374/how-do-i-set-the-defaultfocus-or-defaultbutton-in-a-page-based-on-a-master-page-in-aspnet-20\">http://imar.spaanjaars.com/374/how-do-i-set-the-defaultfocus-or-defaultbutton-in-a-page-based-on-a-master-page-in-aspnet-20</a>','Default form button problem','','inherit','open','open','','322-revision-3','','','2011-01-11 16:16:28','2011-01-11 16:16:28','',322,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/01/11/322-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(350,1,'2011-01-06 16:23:15','2011-01-06 16:23:15','This is a useful tip when you feel like pulling your hair out because you can\'t figure out why the EPiServer site you just published won\'t let you access the CMS. Trying to go to edit mode or admin mode just gives you an error:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-317\" title=\"EPiServer-custom-error\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/EPiServer-custom-error.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"573\" height=\"252\" />\r\n\r\nPage could not be loaded. The link you specified does not work. This may either be the result of temporary maintenance or an incorrect link. Well that\'s not helpful for a developer, so you just need to turn it off to see the ASP.NET error (yellow-screen-of-death).\r\n\r\nSimply set globalErrorHandling=\"Off\" in the &lt;siteSettings&gt; node.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-318\" title=\"Custom-errors-config\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Custom-errors-config.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"642\" height=\"209\" />','Tip: Turn Off EPiServer Custom Error Handling','','inherit','open','open','','316-revision-3','','','2011-01-06 16:23:15','2011-01-06 16:23:15','',316,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/01/06/316-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2011-04-07 07:02:58','2011-04-07 06:02:58','This is a useful tip when you feel like pulling your hair out because you can\'t figure out why the EPiServer site you just published won\'t let you access the CMS. Trying to go to edit mode or admin mode just gives you an error:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-317\" title=\"EPiServer-custom-error\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/EPiServer-custom-error.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"573\" height=\"252\" />\r\n\r\nPage could not be loaded. The link you specified does not work. This may either be the result of temporary maintenance or an incorrect link. Well that\'s not helpful for a developer, so you just need to turn it off to see the ASP.NET error (yellow-screen-of-death).\r\n\r\nSimply set globalErrorHandling=\"Off\" in the &lt;siteSettings&gt; node.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-318\" title=\"Custom-errors-config\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Custom-errors-config.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"642\" height=\"209\" />','Tip: Turn Off EPiServer Custom Error Handling','','inherit','open','open','','316-revision-4','','','2011-04-07 07:02:58','2011-04-07 06:02:58','',316,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/07/316-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(352,1,'2011-04-07 07:04:26','2011-04-07 06:04:26','This is a useful tip when you feel like pulling your hair out because you can\'t figure out why the EPiServer site you just published won\'t let you access the CMS. Trying to go to edit mode or admin mode just gives you an error:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-317\" title=\"EPiServer-custom-error\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/EPiServer-custom-error.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"573\" height=\"252\" />\r\n<blockquote>Page could not be loaded. The link you specified does not work. This may either be the result of temporary maintenance or an incorrect link.</blockquote>\r\nWell that\'s not helpful for a developer, so you just need to turn it off to see the ASP.NET error (yellow-screen-of-death).\r\n\r\nSimply set globalErrorHandling=\"Off\" in the &lt;siteSettings&gt; node.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-318\" title=\"Custom-errors-config\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Custom-errors-config.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"642\" height=\"209\" />','Tip: Turn Off EPiServer Custom Error Handling','','inherit','open','open','','316-revision-5','','','2011-04-07 07:04:26','2011-04-07 06:04:26','',316,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/07/316-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(353,1,'2011-04-07 07:08:04','2011-04-07 06:08:04',' ','','','publish','open','open','','353','','','2011-04-07 07:08:04','2011-04-07 06:08:04','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=353',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(354,1,'2010-09-09 08:53:08','2010-09-09 07:53:08','<div>\r\n\r\nI came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file.\r\n\r\nIn version 4 I had an \"upload\" virtual path which was used for page files and global uploads. As part of the upgrade I separated the page files into their own folder with their own virtual path (/pages/). This creates a problem because all the links in content still point at /upload/ for page files. So you need to add:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;unifiedFileSystem&gt;\r\n	&lt;mappings&gt;\r\n		&lt;map fromPath=\"/upload\" toPath=\"/pages\" type=\"EPiServer.FileSystem.Mapping.PageDirectoryMapping,EPiServer\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nMore info here: <a href=\"../../../en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites</a>\r\n\r\nThen during the upgrade that mapping gets converted to something like this:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;add toPath=\"~/pages/\" fromPath=\"~/upload/\" name=\"Mapping0\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathPageMappingProvider,EPiServer.Legacy4\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nSo the VirtualPahPageMappingProvider is mapping requests for the path /upload/ to path /pages/, it should be last in the list of providers in the configuration if you have another provider handling the /upload/ path.\r\n\r\n</div>','Meeting the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider','I came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file...','inherit','open','open','','212-revision-4','','','2010-09-09 08:53:08','2010-09-09 07:53:08','',212,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/09/212-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(356,1,'2010-05-15 23:11:41','2010-05-15 22:11:41','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files.\r\n\r\nIf you need to override an existing element you can do so, this works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\nTo avoid conflicts with existing language files you could simply create a new XML element to contain your translations, for example:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;mywebsitename&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/mywebsitename&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','Some notes on the EPiServer language XML files and their correct usage.','inherit','open','open','','95-revision-6','','','2010-05-15 23:11:41','2010-05-15 22:11:41','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/95-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(357,1,'2010-07-11 11:00:15','2010-07-11 10:00:15','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.</blockquote>\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">CurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-11','','','2010-07-11 11:00:15','2010-07-11 10:00:15','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/11/35-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(358,1,'2011-04-07 07:10:20','2011-04-07 06:10:20','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.</blockquote>\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">CurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-12','','','2011-04-07 07:10:20','2011-04-07 06:10:20','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/04/07/35-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(359,1,'2011-05-10 18:52:21','2011-05-10 17:52:21','There are a lot of exciting new HTML5 elements to experiment with and I\'ve had the chance to do that this week with a front-end build, which led me to an realisation worth noting.\r\n\r\nI was building a form with 2 date inputs, a start and an end date. Perfect for the new HTML5 date inputs... well that was my first thought. The HTML5 date input (more info at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/forms.html#type-date\">diveintohtml5.org</a>) basically looks like this:\r\n\r\n&lt;input type=\"date\"&gt;\r\n\r\nAnd it has 2 benefits, a browser may (few actually do) render a native date-picker control without the need for any JavaScript, and it tells the browser or search spider that this is a date, a precise point in time... so your mark-up has more <em>meaning</em>.\r\n\r\nSo my date inputs might get date pickers from the browser, but I had to add the JavaScript for other browsers (<a href=\"http://www.modernizr.com/\">Modernizr</a> helps with this sort of thing).\r\n\r\nNext I had to add some code to automatically keep the end date after the start date, a basic convenience for the user, which is easy to do within the JavaScript date-pickers I had added... but what about the native browser date-pickers, I can\'t attach to events from that can I?\r\n\r\nMy realisation was that <strong>I shouldn\'t be using HTML5 date inputs</strong>. My start and end date aren\'t really conveying information about anything. They are empty form elements to be filled in and posted by the user, they are not there to add meaning to information on the site. As for taking advantage of the native date-pickers or any other browser-specific niceties, my dates exist as a pair, they work together and interact, the native date-pickers don\'t do that.','Choosing semantic elements wisely','','publish','open','open','','choosing-semantic-elements-wisely','','','2011-05-10 18:52:21','2011-05-10 17:52:21','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=359',0,'post','',0),(361,1,'2011-05-10 18:38:33','2011-05-10 17:38:33','There are a lot of exciting new HTML5 elements to experiment with and I\'ve had the chance to do that this week with a front-end build, which led me to an realisation worth noting.\n\nI was building a form with 2 date inputs, a start and an end date. Perfect for the new HTML5 date inputs... well that was my first thought.\n\nThe HTML5 date input (more info at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/forms.html#type-date\">diveintohtml5.org</a>) basically looks like this