te and SQL Server database\", finish the wizard steps (ending with database and Alloy Tech site running in IIS)</li>\r\n	<li>Edit the new AlloyTech.csproj and set element &lt;UseIIS&gt; to False, save and open in Visual Studio 2010, and run through the conversion wizard</li>\r\n	<li>Login with a <strong>local </strong>windows account. The site uses the MultiplexingMembershipProvider by default with defers to the SqlServer membership provider and the Windows membership provider</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe next problem is that I want to run this site in Visual Studio\'s built-in development web server. I have <a title=\"EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio development server\" href=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/29/episerver-6-visual-studio-development-server/\">written about problems with this before</a>. So I manually change the config to work for IIS6 - this should fix problems like the Site Center Dashboard showing a 404 error.\r\n\r\nNext I deploy to an IIS6 web server:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remove the bin folder, put it\'s contents in a lib folder and add project references to the contained assemblies (excluding the assembly for the web application itself)</li>\r\n	<li>Set all non-system references to \"copy local\" (so they get copied to the bin folder and do not have to exist on the server)</li>\r\n	<li>Include all the language files in the lang folder so they are published by Visual Studio</li>\r\n	<li>Publish the website and database, including the EPiServer CMS files references by the virtual path providers (I put these in a folder next to the website folder)</li>\r\n	<li>Change the path to the geo ip database in EPiServer.Framework.config</li>\r\n	<li>Update the virtual path provider paths to match the web server</li>\r\n	<li>Log in as administrator and add a user, add WebAdmins and WebEditors groups (grant access to Edit and Admin modes)</li>\r\n	<li>Add permission to the page tree for an editors group</li>\r\n</ol>','Setting up an EPiServer 6 R2 site (in IIS6)','','publish','open','open','','setting-up-an-episerver-6-r2-site-in-iis6','','\nhttp://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/29/episerver-6-visual-studio-development-server/','2011-06-21 17:07:06','2011-06-21 16:07:06','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=384',0,'post','',0),(385,1,'2011-06-21 10:56:28','2011-06-21 09:56:28','These are the steps I follow to create a new EPiServer 6 R2 site. In this case I\'m creating a new demo site for other people in the company to play with or demo to clients. The files are source controlled with Git.\n<ol>\n	<li>First  create a folder structure with a separate folder for the website and another for the virtual path provider files (uploads to the file manager).</li>\n	<li>Run EPiServer deployment center, and select \"Install site and SQL Server database\", finish the wizard steps (ending with database and Alloy Tech site running in IIS)</li>\n	<li>Edit the new AlloyTech.csproj and set element &lt;UseIIS&gt; to False, save and open in Visual Studio 2010, and run through the conversion wizard</li>\n	<li>Login with a <strong>local </strong>windows account. The site uses the MultiplexingMembershipProvider by default with defers to the</li>\n</ol>','Setting up an EPiServer 6 R2 site','','inherit','open','open','','384-revision','','','2011-06-21 10:56:28','2011-06-21 09:56:28','',384,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/06/21/384-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(386,1,'2011-06-21 11:07:03','2011-06-21 10:07:03','These are the steps I follow to create a new EPiServer 6 R2 site. In this case I\'m creating a new demo site for other people in the company to play with or demo to clients. The files are source controlled with Git.\n<ol>\n	<li>First  create a folder structure with a separate folder for the website and another for the virtual path provider files (uploads to the file manager).</li>\n	<li>Run EPiServer deployment center, and select \"Install site and SQL Server database\", finish the wizard steps (endin