ually change the config to work for IIS6 - this should fix problems like the Site Center Dashboard showing a 404 error.\r\n\r\nNext I deploy to an IIS6 web server:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remove the bin folder, put it\'s contents in a lib folder and add project references to the contained assemblies (excluding the assembly for the web application itself)</li>\r\n	<li>Set all non-system references to \"copy local\" (so they get copied to the bin folder and do not have to exist on the server)</li>\r\n	<li>Include all the language files in the lang folder so they are published by Visual Studio</li>\r\n	<li>Publish the website and database, including the EPiServer CMS files references by the virtual path providers (I put these in a folder next to the website folder)</li>\r\n	<li>Change the path to the geo ip database in EPiServer.Framework.config</li>\r\n	<li>Update the virtual path provider paths to match the web server</li>\r\n	<li>Log in as administrator and add a user, add WebAdmins and WebEditors groups</li>\r\n	<li>Add permission to the page tree for WebEditors</li>\r\n</ol>','Setting up an EPiServer 6 R2 site (in IIS6)','','inherit','open','open','','384-revision-6','','','2011-06-21 17:06:27','2011-06-21 16:06:27','',384,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/06/21/384-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(392,1,'2011-06-22 22:08:16','2011-06-22 21:08:16','Allan Thraen of EPiServer has put together a set of mobile templates for EPiServer <a title=\"Mobile Pack on CodePlex\" href=\"http://mobilepack.codeplex.com/\">as an open source project on CodePlex</a>, and <a title=\"EPiServer World article\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Blogs/Allan-Thran/Dates/2011/4/Mobile-Pack-for-EPiServer-CMS/\">written about it on EPiServer World</a>. In this post I look at setting them up on an EPiServer 6 R2 (6.1.379.0) site.\r\n\r\nThe mobile templates are <a title=\"EPiServer NuGet Packages\" href=\" http://nuget.episerver.com\">available as a NuGet package</a>, which is easy enough to install through Visual Studio 2010 <a title=\"Docs for using the package manager\" href=\"http://docs.nuget.org/docs/start-here/managing-nuget-packages-using-the-dialog\">using the Package Manager GUI</a>. Once that\'s downloaded an installed it\'s just a matter of importing the pages and page types, this is done in EPiServer Admin mode. Import the data from the file added by NuGet at mywebsiteroot\\util\\setup\\MobilePack.episerverdata. That gave me a nice set of new mobile pages under my site start page.\r\n<h2>Redirection</h2>\r\nThe next step is redirecting users from the desktop home page to the browser home page. Luckily EPiServer Personalisation allows us to use visitor groups for this. There is already a \"Mobile Users\" visitor group in my demo site, added by NuGet I presume. The language files are missing when I look at this group, so I\'ll copy those into the lang folder manually from the CodePlex download.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-393 alignnone\" title=\"mobile-visitors\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/mobile-visitors.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"987\" height=\"642\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I go to my start page, click on the \"Redirection\" tab (I assume NuGet added this too) and configure the start page to redirect mobile visitors to the mobile pages. I want to test this in <a href=\"http://testiphone.com/\">http://testiphone.com/</a> but it doesn\'t have the correct user agent and will therefore not be redirected to the mobile site. I tried to get around this with a browser switcher plugin for Firefox, but that didn\'t seem to work either. One way to test it is to add a browser like Google Chrome to the visitor group and check the redirect works in Chrome.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Investigating Mobile Pack for EPiServer CMS','','publish','open','open','','investigating-mobile-pack-for-episerver-cms','','','2011-07-01 09:20:00','2011-07-01 08:20:00','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=392',0,'post','',0