tes are <a title=\"EPiServer NuGet Packages\" href=\" http://nuget.episerver.com\">available as a NuGet package</a>, which is easy enough to install through Visual Studio 2010 <a title=\"Docs for using the package manager\" href=\"http://docs.nuget.org/docs/start-here/managing-nuget-packages-using-the-dialog\">using the Package Manager GUI</a>. Once that\'s downloaded an installed it\'s just a matter of importing the pages and page types, this is done in EPiServer Admin mode. Import the data from the file added by NuGet at mywebsiteroot\\util\\setup\\MobilePack.episerverdata. That gave me a nice set of new mobile pages under my site start page.\r\n<h2>Redirection</h2>\r\nThe next step is redirecting users from the desktop home page to the browser home page. Luckily EPiServer Personalisation allows us to use visitor groups for this. There is already a \"Mobile Users\" visitor group in my demo site, added by NuGet I presume. The language files are missing when I look at this group, so I\'ll copy those into the lang folder manually from the CodePlex download.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-393 alignnone\" title=\"mobile-visitors\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/mobile-visitors.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"987\" height=\"642\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I go to my start page, click on the \"Redirection\" tab (I assume NuGet added this too) and configure the start page to redirect mobile visitors to the mobile pages. I want to test this in <a href=\"http://testiphone.com/\">http://testiphone.com/</a> but it doesn\'t have the correct user agent and will therefore not be redirected to the mobile site. I tried to get around this with a browser switcher plugin for Firefox, but that didn\'t seem to work either. One way to test it is to add a browser like Google Chrome to the visitor group and check the redirect works in Chrome.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Investigating Mobile Pack for EPiServer CMS','','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-9','',