ures that are in development at the same time, some may not be ready, while others are done.\n<h2>Cons</h2>\n<strong>Merge headaches.</strong> In a scenario where Jim and Sally are developers who branch from a \"live\" branch to work on different features. Jim may add additional logic to the Invoice class, while Sally uses an opportunity to re-factor the same class. The next week Jim has to deploy both feature branches and tries to merge them back into the \"live\" branch... only to discover his code no longer fits easily into the re-factored Invoice class.','Feature Branches?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2011-07-18 14:55:43','2011-07-18 13:55:43','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=414',0,'post','',0),(415,1,'2011-07-18 14:47:02','2011-07-18 13:47:02','<h2>Pros</h2>\n<strong>Cherry-picking features for deployment.</strong> It is often easy to pick and choose features to integrate with a live branch (or any other). This is useful if we need to deploy a subset of a set features that are in development at the same time, some may not be ready, while others are done.\n<h2>Cons</h2>\n<strong>Merge headaches.</strong> In a scenario where Jim and Sally are developers who branch from a \"live\" branch to work on different features. Jim may add additional logic to the Invoice class, while Sally uses an opportunity to re-factor the same class. The next week Jim has to deploy both feature branches and tries to merge them back into the \"live\" branch... only to discover his code no longer fits easily into the Invoice class.','Feature Branches?','','inherit','open','open','','414-revision','','','2011-07-18 14:47:02','2011-07-18 13:47:02','',414,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2011/07/18/414-revision/',0,'revision','',0);
